{"title_page": "Richard Wershe Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = Richard John Wershe Jr.<ref name=\"dc.state.fl.us\">{{cite web |title=Inmate Population Information Detail |url=http://www.dc.state.fl.us/offenderSearch/detail.aspx?Page=Detail&DCNumber=K70365&TypeSearch=AI |website=Florida Department of Corrections |accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|July 18, 1969 }}\n| birth_place        = [[Michigan]], [[United States]]\n|known for= Youngest F.B.I. informant in history at age 14\n| criminal_charge    = [[Drug possession|Possession]] of cocaine in excess of eight kg\nRacketeering\nRacketeering (Conspiracy to Commit)\n| criminal_penalty   = [[Life imprisonment in the United States|Life in prison]]<br/>\n5 years for racketeering\n| criminal_status    = Paroled (2017)\nImprisoned (2017)\nScheduled Release Date: December 25th, 2020.\n}}\n\n'''Richard Wershe Jr.''' (born July 18, 1969),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdocweb.state.mi.us/otis2/otis2profile.aspx?mdocNumber=192034%20|title=BIOGRAPHICAL INFORMATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Michigan Department of Corrections|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> also known as '''White Boy Rick''', is the youngest known [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|Federal Bureau of Investigation (F.B.I.)]] [[informant]] ever, having worked with the bureau at only age 14.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/white-boy-rick-casts-richie-merritt-ricky-wershe-matthew-mcconaughey-1202000245/|title=Newcomer Richie Merritt Lands Title Role in 'White Boy Rick' Opposite Matthew McConaughey|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=March 3, 2017|work=Variety}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nWershe and his [[lower middle-class]] family lived in a neighborhood on [[List of neighborhoods in Detroit#East|the east side of Detroit]] about seven miles from downtown. They lived there during a period in the late 1980 and early 1990s when Detroit and many other major American cities were gaining widespread reputations for crime and violence, largely due to an influx of cocaine and the emergence of the crack cocaine epidemic.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/movies/2018/09/05/white-boy-rick-richard-wershe/1192983002/|title=Who is White Boy Rick? 7 facts about the 14-year-old FBI informant|last=Daalder|first=Marc|date=September 5, 2018|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Wershe's father was also an FBI informant and first reported to the police and the federal agency alongside him before going solo.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe name \"White Boy Rick\" was not a street name that Wershe used himself, nor was it one he was ever called by those with whom he associated. The name was instead given to him by reporters who covered his case.<ref name=\":1\" /> When Wershe was 16, the FBI no longer needed him, so he began selling [[cocaine]] himself without the FBI's knowledge. \n\nIn 1987 Wershe was arrested for possessing cocaine in excess of eight kilograms (17.6 pounds).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/white-boy-ricks-parole-hearing-and-drug-war-lessons-unlearned|title=White Boy Rick's Parole Hearing and Drug War Lessons Unlearned|first=Evan|last=Hughes|date=June 27, 2017|work=The New Yorker}}</ref>  He was sentenced to [[life in prison]] in [[Michigan]] under the state's 650-Lifer Law, a drug statute that penalized those found in possession of more than 650 grams (22.92&nbsp;oz) of cocaine or heroin with life imprisonment without parole.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-is-white-boy-rick-in-2018-richard-wershe-jr-has-had-eventful-life-11861008|title=Here's Where White Boy Rick Is Now, Years After His FBI Involvement|last=Tenreyro|first=Tatiana|date=September 14, 2018|website=Bustle|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Wershe earned [[parole]] in 2017 after nearly 30 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/defenders/white-boy-rick-wershe-is-granted-parole-in-michigan-after-nearly-30-years-in-prison|title='White Boy' Rick Wershe is granted parole in Michigan after nearly 30 years in prison|first1=Kevin|last1=Dietz|first2=Dave Jr|last2=Bartkowiak|first3=Derick|last3=Hutchinson|date=July 15, 2017|publisher=ClickOnDetroit}}</ref> He was released from the Oaks Correction Facility in Michigan in April 2017 and turned over to U.S. Marshals.\n\nWershe is being housed at TTH Kissimee FL<ref name=\"dc.state.fl.us\">{{cite web |title=Inmate Population Information Detail |url=http://www.dc.state.fl.us/offenderSearch/detail.aspx?Page=Detail&DCNumber=K70365&TypeSearch=AI |website=Florida Department of Corrections |accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref> after spending nearly three decades behind bars in Michigan as a nonviolent drug offender. He was housed at [[Florida State Prison]] after pleading guilty to being involved in a [[car theft]] ring. Wershe says he pleaded guilty to protect his mother and sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/white-boy-rick-wershe-is-now-housed-at-florida-state-prison|title='White Boy' Rick Wershe is now housed at Florida state prison|last=Bartkowiak Jr|first=Dave|last2=Dietz|first2=Kevin|work=[[WDIV-TV]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, his application for an early release was denied by the Florida clemency board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2019/04/10/white-boy-rick-denied-early-release-florida/3419625002/|title='White Boy Rick' denied early release in Florida|last=Hicks|first=Mark|last2=Rahal|first2=Sarah|date=April 11, 2019|website=Detroit News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\nA film based on his life, titled ''[[White Boy Rick]]'', was released in September 14, 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/06/04/white-boy-rick-watch-exclusive-first-trailer-starring-matthew-mcconaughey/666882002/|title=See Matthew McConaughey fail tragically as a dad in exclusive 'White Boy Rick' trailer|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=June 4, 2018|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en}}</ref> The documentary chronicling the case of Richard Wershe Jr., ''[[White Boy (Documentary)|White Boy]]'', won the 2017 FREEP Film Festival Audience Choice Award. It was released in 2017 and began airing on the Starz network in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== {{Authority control}}External links ==\n\n* [https://richardwershejr.blogspot.com/ Richard Wershe Jr. Blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wershe, Richard}}\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation informants]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n{{Detroit-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = Richard John Wershe Jr.<ref name=\"dc.state.fl.us\">{{cite web |title=Inmate Population Information Detail |url=http://www.dc.state.fl.us/offenderSearch/detail.aspx?Page=Detail&DCNumber=K70365&TypeSearch=AI |website=Florida Department of Corrections |accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|July 18, 1969 }}\n| birth_place        = [[Michigan]], [[United States]]\n|known for= Youngest F.B.I. informant in history at age 14\n| criminal_charge    = [[Drug possession|Possession]] of cocaine in excess of eight kg\nRacketeering\nRacketeering (Conspiracy to Commit)\n| criminal_penalty   = [[Life imprisonment in the United States|Life in prison]]<br/>\n5 years for racketeering\n| criminal_status    = Paroled (2017)\nImprisoned (2017)\nScheduled Release Date: December 25th, 2020.\n}}\n\n'''Richard Wershe Jr.''' (born July 18, 1969),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mdocweb.state.mi.us/otis2/otis2profile.aspx?mdocNumber=192034%20|title=BIOGRAPHICAL INFORMATION|last=|first=|date=|website=Michigan Department of Corrections|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> also known as '''White Boy Rick''', is the youngest known [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|Federal Bureau of Investigation (F.B.I.)]] [[informant]] ever, having worked with the bureau at only age 14.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/white-boy-rick-casts-richie-merritt-ricky-wershe-matthew-mcconaughey-1202000245/|title=Newcomer Richie Merritt Lands Title Role in 'White Boy Rick' Opposite Matthew McConaughey|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=March 3, 2017|work=Variety}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nWershe and his [[lower middle-class]] family lived in a neighborhood on [[List of neighborhoods in Detroit#East|the east side of Detroit]] about seven miles from downtown. They lived there during a period in the late 1980 and early 1990s when Detroit and many other major American cities were gaining widespread reputations for crime and violence, largely due to an influx of cocaine and the emergence of the crack cocaine epidemic.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/movies/2018/09/05/white-boy-rick-richard-wershe/1192983002/|title=Who is White Boy Rick? 7 facts about the 14-year-old FBI informant|last=Daalder|first=Marc|date=September 5, 2018|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Wershe's father was also an FBI informant and first reported to the police and the federal agency alongside him before going solo.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe name \"White Boy Rick\" was not a street name that Wershe used himself, nor was it one he was ever called by those with whom he associated. The name was instead given to him by reporters who covered his case.<ref name=\":1\" /> When Wershe was 16, the FBI no longer needed him, so he began selling [[cocaine]] himself without the FBI's knowledge. \n\nIn 1987 Wershe was arrested for possessing cocaine in excess of eight kilograms (17.6 pounds).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/white-boy-ricks-parole-hearing-and-drug-war-lessons-unlearned|title=White Boy Rick's Parole Hearing and Drug War Lessons Unlearned|first=Evan|last=Hughes|date=June 27, 2017|work=The New Yorker}}</ref>  He was sentenced to [[life in prison]] in [[Michigan]] under the state's 650-Lifer Law, a drug statute that penalized those found in possession of more than 650 grams (22.92&nbsp;oz) of cocaine or heroin with life imprisonment without parole.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-is-white-boy-rick-in-2018-richard-wershe-jr-has-had-eventful-life-11861008|title=Here's Where White Boy Rick Is Now, Years After His FBI Involvement|last=Tenreyro|first=Tatiana|date=September 14, 2018|website=Bustle|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Wershe earned [[parole]] in 2017 after nearly 30 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/defenders/white-boy-rick-wershe-is-granted-parole-in-michigan-after-nearly-30-years-in-prison|title='White Boy' Rick Wershe is granted parole in Michigan after nearly 30 years in prison|first1=Kevin|last1=Dietz|first2=Dave Jr|last2=Bartkowiak|first3=Derick|last3=Hutchinson|date=July 15, 2017|publisher=ClickOnDetroit}}</ref> He was released from the Oaks Correction Facility in Michigan in April 2017 and turned over to U.S. Marshals.\n\nWershe is being housed at TTH Kissimee FL <ref>name=\"dc.state.fl.us\">{{cite web |title=Inmate Population Information Detail |url=http://www.dc.state.fl.us/offenderSearch/detail.aspx?Page=Detail&DCNumber=K70365&TypeSearch=AI |website=Florida Department of Corrections |accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref> after spending nearly three decades behind bars in Michigan as a nonviolent drug offender. He was housed at [[Florida State Prison]] after pleading guilty to being involved in a [[car theft]] ring. Wershe says he pleaded guilty to protect his mother and sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/white-boy-rick-wershe-is-now-housed-at-florida-state-prison|title='White Boy' Rick Wershe is now housed at Florida state prison|last=Bartkowiak Jr|first=Dave|last2=Dietz|first2=Kevin|work=[[WDIV-TV]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, his application for an early release was denied by the Florida clemency board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2019/04/10/white-boy-rick-denied-early-release-florida/3419625002/|title='White Boy Rick' denied early release in Florida|last=Hicks|first=Mark|last2=Rahal|first2=Sarah|date=April 11, 2019|website=Detroit News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\nA film based on his life, titled ''[[White Boy Rick]]'', was released in September 14, 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/06/04/white-boy-rick-watch-exclusive-first-trailer-starring-matthew-mcconaughey/666882002/|title=See Matthew McConaughey fail tragically as a dad in exclusive 'White Boy Rick' trailer|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=June 4, 2018|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en}}</ref> The documentary chronicling the case of Richard Wershe Jr., ''[[White Boy (Documentary)|White Boy]]'', won the 2017 FREEP Film Festival Audience Choice Award. It was released in 2017 and began airing on the Starz network in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== {{Authority control}}External links ==\n\n* [https://richardwershejr.blogspot.com/ Richard Wershe Jr. Blog]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wershe, Richard}}\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation informants]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n\n\n{{Crime-stub}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n{{Detroit-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Peter NYC", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Fixing style/layout errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Wershe_Jr."}
{"title_page": "List of equipment of the Indian Army", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\nThis is a list of some of the modern and historical '''equipment used by the [[Indian Army]]'''. Most of the army equipment is of foreign design and produced under licence in India but efforts are on to progressively design and manufacture equipment locally. The 41 [[Indian Ordnance Factories]] under control of [[Ordnance Factories Board]] manufacture most of the Army equipment like [[small arms]], [[ammunition]], [[combat vehicle]]s, [[artillery]], [[tank]]s etc.\n\n==Infantry weapons ==\n\n===Small Arms===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\" | Name\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Weapon\n! style=\"width:15%;\" | Type\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | Caliber\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Origin\n! Notes\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |Handguns\n|-\n|[[Pistol Auto 9mm 1A]]\n|[[File:Pistol Auto 9 mm 1A - Kolkata 2012-01-23 8779.JPG|[[Pistol Auto 9mm 1A]]|150px]]||[[Semi-automatic pistol]]||[[9mm Parabellum|9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{CAN}}<br>{{IND}}||'''Status: In service.''' Standard side-arm of the Indian Army, manufactured under license.\n|-\n|[[SIG Sauer P226]]<ref>https://sites.google.com/site/worldinventory/wiw_as_india</ref>\n|[[File:SIG P226 img 1624.jpg|150px]]||[[Semi-automatic pistol]]||[[9mm Parabellum|9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{GER}}||'''Status: In service.''' Used by NSG.\n|-\n|[[Glock 17]]\n|[[File:Glock17.jpg|Glock 17|150px]]||[[Semi-automatic pistol]]||[[9mm Parabellum|9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{AUT}}||'''Status: In service.''' Standard Special Forces pistol.\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |Shotgun\n|-\n|[[Franchi SPAS-15]]\n|[[File:SPAS15.jpg|Franchi SPAS-15 Combat Shotgun|150px]]||[[Combat Shotgun]]|| 18.5 x 76&nbsp;mm NATO ||{{ITA}}||'''Status: In service.''' Used by special forces, which includes NSG.\n|-\n|[[OFB pump action Shotgun]]\n|[[File:6--sa12pagun.jpg|thumb]]\n|[[pump action]]\n|[[12-gauge shotgun]]\n|{{IND}}\n|'''Status:In Service'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |SMGs\n|-\n|[[Sterling submachine gun|SAF Carbine 2A1]]\n|[[File:Sterling SMG.JPG|[[SAF Carbine 2A1]]|150px]]||[[Submachine gun]]||[[9mm Parabellum|9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{IND}}<br>{{GBR}}||'''Status: In service/will be Replaced.''' [[submachine gun|SAF Carbine 1A]]. To be replaced by the [[Modern Sub Machine Carbine|MSMC]].\n|-\n|[[Uzi#Military variants|Micro-Uzi]]\n|[[File:Uzi of the israeli armed forces.jpg|Micro-Uzi|150px]]||[[Submachine gun]]||[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{ISR}}||'''Status: In service.''' For use by Special Forces. Micro-Uzi variant used.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/LAND-FORCES/Army/Galleries/50-5/0548.jpg |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010190951/http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/LAND-FORCES/Army/Galleries/50-5/0548.jpg |archivedate=10 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}?</ref>\n|-\n|[[Heckler & Koch MP5]]\n|[[File:Heckler & Koch MP5-1.jpg|MP5 Submachine Gun|150px]]||[[Submachine gun]]||[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{GER}}||'''Status: In service.''' Used by Indian Army Special Forces\n|-\n|[[Br\u00fcgger & Thomet MP9]]\n|[[File:B&T MP9 SMG.JPG|MP9 machine pistol|150px]]||[[Machine pistol]]||[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]||{{CHE}}||'''Status: In service.''' Used by [[Ghatak Force|Ghatak Platoon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20121112/main4.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Main News|website=www.tribuneindia.com|access-date=2016-10-27}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |Assault Rifles\n|-\n|[[Steyr AUG]]\n|[[File:Steyr-AUG.jpeg|150px]]\n|[[Assault Rifle|Assault Rifle/Sub Machine Gun]]\n|[[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]] and [[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]](SMG Variant)\n|{{AUT}}\n|'''Status: In service.''' Used by special forces in small numbers.\n|-\n|[[FN SCAR]]\n|[[File:Scar L Standard.jpg|150px]]\n|[[Assault rifle]]\n|[[5.56\u00d745mm N