how 2007-06-24 n25.jpg|170px]]  || {{Flagu|Israel}} || [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle]] || || 40 ||\n|-\n| [[IAI Harop]]    || [[File:IAI Harop PAS 2013 01.jpg|170px]]  || {{Flagu|Israel}} || [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle]] || || 110+<ref>https://www.debka.com/mivzak/indian-air-force-buys-another-54-israeli-harop-drones/</ref> || 54 more on order \n|-\n|[[DRDO Rustom|DRDO Rustom 2]]||[[File:DRDO Rustom.JPG|170px]] ||{{Flagu|India}}|| [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle]] || || ||'''Status: Under Development/Undergoing Trials.''' First flight held on November 16, 2016.\n|}\n\n==Radar==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Name \n!Image\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Type \n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Quantity \n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Origin \n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Rajendra Radar|Rajendra]] \n|[[File:Rajendra Radar by BEL image.jpg|center|frameless]]||[[Passive electronically scanned array|Passive electronically scanned array radar]] ||  || {{Flagu|India}} || '''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|[[Indian Doppler Radar|INDRA]]\n|[[File:Sri Lanka Military 0257.jpg|cente|frameless]]\n|[[Passive electronically scanned array|Passive electronically scanned array radar]]\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|[[Swathi Weapon Locating Radar]]\n|[[File:WLR Mockup.jpg|cente|frameless]]\n|[[Artillery locating radar|Artillery Locating Radar]]\n|28\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|[[Central acquisition radar (3D-CAR)|Rohini]]\n|[[File:Rohini radar at 2010 Republic Day Parade.jpg|cente|frameless]]\n|[[3D radar]]\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|[[Samyukta Electronic Warfare System|Samyukta]]\n|\n|[[Electronic warfare|Electronic Warfare]]\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|Bharani\n|\n|Low Level Light weight 2D Radar\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|Multi Mission Radar\n|\n|Multi Mission Radar\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Development .\n|-\n|Short Range Battle Field Surveillance Radar\n|\n|Short Range [[Battlefield surveillance radar|Battle Field Surveillance Radar]] \n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Inducted  .\n|-\n|[[Radar imaging|Through wall detection Radar]]\n|\n|[[Radar imaging|Through wall detection Radar]]\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Development . Prototype ready.\n|-\n|[[Ground-penetrating radar|Ground Penetration Radar]]\n|\n|[[Ground-penetrating radar|Ground Penetration Radar]]\n|\n|{{Flagu|India}}\n|'''Status:''' Development . Prototype ready.\n|}\n\n==Future procurements==\n\n===Vehicles===\n* BMP-2 based AKASH SAM carrier production started at [[Ordnance Factory Medak]].\n* BMP-2 based NBC protected recon vehicle to be manufactured at [[Ordnance Factory Medak]].\n* Light Specialist Vehicle \u2013 LSV with mounting provision for MMG to be purchased by Infantry division.\n* Indian Army has shown interest in TATA LAMV(Light Armoured Multipurpose Vehicle) with mounting provision of MMG, BFSR, HHTI to be purchased by Mechanized Forces. It is slated to be future ready for Battlefield Management System (BMS).\n* Future Infantry Combat Vehicle - 2600 FICV to be procured to replace old BMP-2s. Initially, GoI asked different private and public sector companies to delevelop FICV. But, it seems that the plan to develop new vehicle is put on hold due to budgetary cuts. Instead, upgradation of old BMP-2s with new powerful engines, transmission and new [[Kliver turret]] with 30mm gun and four [[Kornet-M]] ATGM launchers in being tried.\n* [[Armoured Personnel Carrier]] - 100 APC to be procured for United Nations peace keeping missions.\n* 1586 vehicles to be procured to mount ATGMs on these.\n* 1770 Future Ready Combat Vehicle to replace the T-72 MBT's. The tanks would have 120/125mm smooth bore gun, be in medium weight class (50 tonnes) with a crew of 3/4 personnel.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianarmy.nic.in/writereaddata/RFI/542/RFI%20FRCV%2008%20Nov%2017.pdf|title=Indian Army FRCV RFI|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Artillery and missile systems===\nUnder the Field Artillery Rationalization Plan, Indian Army plans to procure 3000 to 4000 155&nbsp;mm towed, wheeled and tracked artillery systems.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} The requirement for artillery guns to be met with indigenous development and production.<ref>{{cite web |author=Business Standard |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/155-mm-gun-contract-drdo-entersfray/402834/ |title=155-mm gun contract: DRDO enters the fray |publisher=Business-standard.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-21}}</ref> Production of crucial bi-modular charge system will be started soon at Nalanda ordnance factory. HEMRL, a DRDO lab has developed the technology indigenously.<ref>{{cite web |author=the hindu businessline |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and.../article3342018.ece |title=Nalanda Ordnance Factory Board developing indigenous artillery shells |publisher=the hindu.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-13 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* State-run Ordnance Factory Board (OFB) will deliver two types of indigenously developed 155mm howitzers to the Indian Army based on the [[FH 77|FH77B]] howitzer purchased way back in 1986. One version will be 155/39 calibre while the other will be 155/45 calibre. Trials are to be completed by June 2013\n*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army-technology.com/news/newsindian-ofb-soon-deliver-artillery-guns-user-trials |title=Indian OFB soon to deliver artillery guns for user trials |publisher=Army Technology |date= |accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> Government is also evaluating 155mm/52 self-propelled howitzers wherein three Indian vendors, including two private sector companies, have been selected for trials of their equipment. \n*[[Agni missile system|Agni-V]] \u2013 Intercontinental version of the Agni missile system. The missile was test fired for the first time on 19 April 2012 and was inducted in 2014.\n*[[Bharat Dynamics|Bharat Dynamics Limited]] has tested Second Generation Amogha [[anti-tank missile]]s with a range of 2.8&nbsp;km(Tested).This [[anti-tank missile]] will be handed to the Indian Army after some trials.\n*[[Defence Research and Development Organisation|DRDO]] will start working on [[Man-portable anti-tank systems|Man portable]] [[Nag (missile)|Nag]] [[Anti-tank missile|anti tank missile]].\n\n===Infantry equipment===\n\n*AK-203 - 750,000 rifles to be manufactured locally by OFB. It will be the standard weapon of Indian Army replacing INSAS, expected follow on orders from paramilitary and state police.\n*Caracal International CAR 816 - Order placed for 94,000 units of CAR 816 carbine.\n*[[Modern Sub Machine Carbine]] - to replace the Indian [[Sterling submachine gun]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenseworld.net/go/defensenews.jsp?id=4106 |title=DRDO to display sub-machine carbine at Defexpo 2010 |publisher=Defenseworld.net |accessdate=2012-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723085406/http://www.defenseworld.net/go/defensenews.jsp?id=4106 |archivedate=23 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*Indian Army has requirement for 300,000 modular body armour and ballistic helmets primarily for their Infantry regiments. RFI's have been issued.\n*1000 Anti materiel rifles are to acquired for which global RFI's have been issued by the MOD.\n* [[Sniper Rifles]] - 5000 new sniper rifles in [[.338 Lapua Magnum]] to be procured to replace old [[Dragunov SVD]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/indian-army-looking-for-a-deadlier-sniper-rifle-to-replace-ageing-draganov-266996.html |title=Indian Army Looking For A Deadlier Sniper Rifle To Replace Ageing Draganov |publisher=Indiatimes|date=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Ballistic helmet]]-Indian army has ordered about 158,000 (1.58 Lakh) ballistic helmets from Kanpur-based defence firm [[MKU (company)|MKU]]. The Indian Government has approved procurement of 328,000 (3.28 Lakh) ballistic helmets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/army-gets-the-first-lot-of-7500-hi-tech-helmets/articleshow/59585896.cms|title=Army gets the first lot of 7,500 hi-tech helmets|last=Gurung|first=Shaurya Karanbir|date=2018-07-13|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n*[[Bulletproof vest]]-The Ministry of Defence ordered 186,138 (1.86 Lakh) bulletproof vests on April 9, 2018. These will be manufactured in India by SMPP Pvt Ltd. This is in addition to the 50,000 vests ordered in 2016 under emergency procurement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/army-bulletproof-jackets-make-in-india-1208531-2018-04-09|title=Army soldiers get 1.86 lakh new bulletproof jackets after 9-year wait|date=9 April 2018|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\n===Aviation===\n* '''Light Utility Helicopter''': The Indian army has projected a requirement for up to 197 light helicopters to replace its ageing fleet of [[A\u00e9rospatiale Alouette III|Chetaks]] and [[A\u00e9rospatiale Alouette II|Cheetahs]]. The Indian Army chose [[Eurocopter Fennec|Eurocopter AS 550]] under a US$550 million contract in summer of 2007. Under this contract 60 helicopters were to be supplied from Eurocopter in fly-away condition and the rest were to be assembled by HAL in India. This order was later scrapped due to allegations of unfair field trials from one of the competing company, Bell Helicopters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaenews.com/india/20071206/84767.htm |title=Indian Army tender for 197 Eurocopter Fennec helicopters Scrapped |publisher=Indiaenews.com |date=6 December 2007 |accessdate=2012-04-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.indiaprwire.com/businessnews/20070408/21846.htm Eurocopter wins big Indian Army deal] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615212045/http://www.indiaprwire.com/businessnews/20070408/21846.htm |date=15 June 2007 }}</ref> A fresh tender process was initiated later in which [[Eurocopter Fennec]] and [[Kamov Ka-226]] were shortlisted for user trials. Trials were completed and [[Kamov Ka-226]] was declared winner and about 200 helicopters are to be made in India under the \"[[Make in India]]\" initiative, Indian Army have planned to replace obsolete [[A\u00e9rospatiale Alouette III|Chetaks]] and [[A\u00e9rospatiale Alouette II|Cheetahs]] with it, until the arrival of [[HAL Light Utility Helicopter|HAL LUH]], as the later would be ready for its first flight only by 2017.\n* '''HAL Light Combat Helicopter''' - HAL has obtained a firm order to deliver 114 HAL Light Combat Helicopters to the Indian Army.<ref>Shenoy, Ramnath. [http://www.ptinews.com/news/422197_India-to-test-fly-light-combat-helicopters-shortly \"India to test fly light combat helicopters shortly\"]. [[Press Trust of India]], 14 December 2009. Retrieved 4 January 2010. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218083937/http://www.ptinews.com/news/422197_India-to-test-fly-light-combat-helicopters-shortly |date=18 December 2009 }}</ref>\n* '''Boeing AH-64 Apache''' - The [[Government of India]] approved the purchase of 6 helicopters in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://m-ndtv-com.cdn.ampproject.org/c/m.ndtv.com/india-news/army-to-get-its-first-attack-helicopters-apache-deal-worth-655-million-1738867?amp=1&akamai-rum=off |title=For First Time, Army To Get Its Own Attack Helicopters, Boeing Apaches |website=NDTV |date= |access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref><ref>[http://defencenews.in/article/Indian-Army-asked-for-11-Apaches,-but-got-only-6-283793 ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824081539/http://www.defencenews.in/article/Indian-Army-asked-for-11-Apaches,-but-got-only-6-283793 |date=24 August 2017 }}. Defense News</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n[[File:TATA LPTA 1615 TC.jpg|none|thumb|TATA LPTA 1615 on board freight train at Surat railway station]]\n\n<gallery>\nFile:IA Artillery.jpg|[[Indian Army]] [[artillery]] gun\