inistry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, at Wayback Machine.}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 4,709\n| area_rank               = [[Provinces of Thailand|Ranked 45th]]\n| area_water_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"TDD\">{{cite web ||url=http://stat.bora.dopa.go.th/stat/statnew/statTDD/ |title=\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e08\u0e33\u0e19\u0e27\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e08\u0e33\u0e1b\u0e35 \u0e1e.\u0e28.2561 |date=31 December 2018 |department=Registration Office Department of the Interior, Ministry of the Interior |language=Thai |trans-title=Statistics, population and house statistics for the year 2018 |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 473,738\n| population_as_of        = 2018\n| population_rank         = [[Provinces of Thailand| Ranked 59th]]\n| population_density_km2  = 101\n| population_density_rank = [[Provinces of Thailand|Ranked 49th]]\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = Human Achievement Index\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"HAI 2560\">[[:File:Human achievement index 2017.pdf|Human achievement index 2017 by National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB), pages 1-40, maps 1-9, retrieved 14 September 2019, ISBN 978-974-9769-33-1]]</ref>\n| demographics1_title1    = HAI (2017)\n| demographics1_info1     = 0.5465&nbsp;\"low\"<br/>[[Krabi Province#Human achievement index 2017|Ranked 66th]]\n| timezone1               = [[Time in Thailand|ICT]]\n| utc_offset1             = +7\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in Thailand|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 81xxx\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Thailand|Calling code]]\n| area_code               = 075\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:TH|TH-81]]\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.krabi.go.th}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Krabi''' ({{lang-th|\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48}} {{IPA-th|kr\u0101.b\u00ec\u02d0|pron}}, {{lang-sou|\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48}} {{IPA-th|kra.bi\u02d0|pron}}) is one of the southern [[Provinces of Thailand|provinces]] (''changwat'') of [[Thailand]], on the shore of the [[Andaman Sea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andaman Sea |url=https://www.google.com/maps/@7.6069786,98.3760131,9.25z |website=Google Maps |accessdate=2018-12-15}}</ref> Neighbouring provinces are (from north clockwise) [[Phang Nga province|Phang Nga]], [[Surat Thani province|Surat Thani]], [[Nakhon Si Thammarat province|Nakhon Si Thammarat]], and [[Trang province|Trang]]. [[Phuket Province]] lies to the west across [[Phang Nga Bay]]. [[Krabi]] town is the seat of provincial government.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Poda Island panorama.jpg|thumb|left|370px|Ko Poda seen from Ko Thap]]\nThe area is dotted with solitary [[limestone]] peaks, both on land and in the sea. Rock climbers from all over travel to Ton Sai Beach and [[Railay Beach]]. The beaches form part of Krabi's [[Phra Nang Peninsula]]. Of the 154 islands in the province, [[Ko Phi Phi Le]] is the most famous, as it was the site of the movie ''[[The Beach (film)|The Beach]]''. Other notable islands include [[Ko Phi Phi Don]], part of the [[Phi Phi Islands]], and [[Ko Lanta]], a larger island to the south. The coast was damaged by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|tsunami of 26 December 2004]].\n\nKrabi's limestone hills contain many caves, most having [[stalactite]]s and [[stalagmite]]s. Tham Chao Le and [[Tham Phi Hua To]], both in [[Amphoe Ao Luek|Ao Luek District]], contain prehistoric rock-paintings depicting humans, animals, and geometrical shapes. In Lang Rong Rien cave in 1986 archaeologists found 40,000-year-old human artifacts: stone tools, pottery, and bones. It is one of the oldest traces of human occupation in Southeast Asia. Krabi's caves are one of the main sources of nests of the [[Swiftlet|edible-nest swiftlet]], used in the making of [[bird's nest soup]].<ref>{{cite web|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e25\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21 \u201c\u0e40\u0e25\u0e47\u0e01 \u0e2a\u0e15\u0e39\u0e25\u201d \u0e04\u0e27\u0e49\u0e32\u0e23\u0e31\u0e07\u0e19\u0e01\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48|url= https://www.thairath.co.th/content/532679|language=thai|date=2015-10-16|work=[[Thairath]]}}</ref>\n\nKrabi's farmland is dominated by a [[duopoly]] of [[natural rubber|rubber]] and [[palm oil]] plantations. Palm plantations alone occupy 980,000 [[rai (area)|rai]] (1,568&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), or 52 percent of the province's farmland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atthakor|first1=Ploenpote|title=Govt needs to get fired up over renewables|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1066584/govt-needs-to-get-fired-up-over-renewables|accessdate=20 August 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Together, palm oil and rubber cover 95 percent of Krabi's cultivated area with many smallholder farms amidst industrial plantations.<ref name=\"WWF\">{{cite book|last1=World Wildlife Fund Greater Mekong Program (WWF-GMP)|last2=South East Asian-Global Change System for Analysis, Research and Training organisation (SEA-START)|title=Climate Change Impacts in Krabi Province, Thailand. A study of environmental, social, and economic challenges|date=December 2008|url=http://startcc.iwlearn.org/doc/Doc_eng_11.pdf|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>{{RP|5}}\n\n==History==\nCirca 1200 CE, Krabi was tributary to the [[Thammarat kingdom|Kingdom of Ligor]], a city on the Kra Peninsula's east coast, better known today as Nakhon Si Thammarat. In modern times, Krabi was administered from Nakhon Si Thammarat, even after 1872 when King [[Chulalongkorn]] granted Krabi town status. In 1875 it was made a direct subordinate of Bangkok, becoming what is now a province. In 1900 the governor <!--[[Ratsadanupradit Mahison Phakdi|Phraya Ratsada Nupradit]] (Kho Sim Be na Ranong) --> moved the seat of the province from Ban Talad Kao to its present location at the mouth of the Krabi River.\n\nIt is believed the town may have taken its name from the word \"krabi\", which means 'sword'. This may stem from a legend that an ancient sword was unearthed prior to the city's founding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srikrabi.net/en/knowledge-detail.php?id=83|work=srikrabi|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48|language=thai}}</ref>\n\n==Symbols==\nThe [[Seals of The Provinces of Thailand|seal of the province]] shows two ancient crossed swords ([[krabi (sword)|''krabi'']] is a word for an ancient Siamese sword) in front of the [[Indian Ocean]] and [[Khao Phanom Bencha]] mountain which, at {{convert|1397|m|-1}} above sea level, is the highest mountain of the province.<ref name=OSMA>{{cite web|title=Symbol of Krabi|url=http://www.osmsouth-w.moi.go.th/osm-introduce.php?url=krabi-logo&l=en|website=OSM Andamnan: The Office of Strategy Management for Southern Province Cluster|accessdate=26 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234115/http://www.osmsouth-w.moi.go.th/osm-introduce.php?url=krabi-logo&l=en|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe provincial slogan is, \"Krabi, the liveable city, friendly people.\"<ref name=OSMA />\n\nThe provincial tree is the ''blue sky'' (Thai: thung-fa \u0e17\u0e38\u0e49\u0e07\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32) or ''[[Alstonia macrophylla]]''.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n===Provincial government===\nKrabi is subdivided into eight districts (''[[amphoe]]''), which are further divided into 53 subdistricts (''[[tambon]]'') and 374 villages (''[[muban]]'').\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Map\n! Number\n! Name\n! Thai\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[File:Amphoe Krabi.svg|170px]]\n|-\n||1||[[Amphoe Mueang Krabi|Mueang Krabi]]|| \u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48\n|-\n||2||[[Amphoe Khao Phanom|Khao Phanom]]|| \u0e40\u0e02\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e19\u0e21\n|-\n||3||[[Ko Lanta]] || \u0e40\u0e01\u0e32\u0e30\u0e25\u0e31\u0e19\u0e15\u0e32\n|-\n||4||[[Amphoe Khlong Thom|Khlong Thom]]|| \u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e21 \n|-\n||5||[[Amphoe Ao Luek|Ao Luek]]|| \u0e2d\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e25\u0e36\u0e01\n|-\n||6||[[Amphoe Plai Phraya|Plai Phraya]]|| \u0e1b\u0e25\u0e32\u0e22\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e22\u0e32\n|-\n||7||[[Amphoe Lam Thap|Lam Thap]]|| \u0e25\u0e33\u0e17\u0e31\u0e1a\n|-\n||8||[[Amphoe Nuea Khlong|Nuea Khlong]]|| \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\n|}\n===Local government===\nAs of 26 November 2019 there are<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dla.go.th/work/abt/province.jsp |title=Number of local government organizations by province |date=26 November 2019 |website=dla.go.th |publisher=Department of Local Administration (DLA) |access-date=10 December 2019 | quote=1 Krabi: 1 PAO, 1 Town mun., 12 Subdistrict mun., 48 SAO.}}</ref>: one Krabi Provincial Administration Organisation (''ongkan borihan suan changwat'') and 13 municipal (''thesaban'') areas in the province. Krabi has town (''[[thesaban mueang]]'') status. Further 12 subdistrict municipalities (''[[thesaban tambon]]''). The non-municipal areas are administered by 48 Subdistrict Administrative Organisations - SAO (''ongkan borihan suan tambon'').<ref name=\"TDD\"/>\n\n== Population and culture ==\nKrabi's population includes Buddhists, Thai-Chinese, [[Moken|Moken (sea gypsies)]], and Muslims. Population is most dense in the coastal area in [[Nuea Khlong District]] and [[Mueang Krabi District|Krabi city districts]], both with population densities above 150 people per km<sup>2</sup>. The least densely populated area is the inland mountain [[Khao Phanom District]] at 61 persons per km<sup>2</sup>. Buddhism is the religion most observed (66 percent) followed by Islam (33 percent). Krabi has been little affected by the Muslim militant insurgency that has plagued the southern provinces of Thailand since 2003. Traditionally Krabi's inhabitants worked in agriculture, for the province is rich in rubber, palm oil, and oranges. In recent years tourism has become an important source of income.<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|7}}\n\n==Economy==\nAgriculture, tourism, and, to a lesser extent, fisheries, form the backbone of Krabi's economy.<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|18\u201319}} Rubber is the primary cash crop of the province, followed by palm oil. Thailand's largest producer of palm oil products, Univanich Palm Oil PCL, is headquartered in Krabi. It employs 1,000 persons directly and purchases feed stock from 2,000 small and medium-sized Krabi growers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://univanich.com/product.htm|website=Univanich Palm Oil PCL|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Ko Phi Phi after sunset, preparing for the night.JPG|thumb|Sunset, Ko Phi Phi]]\nKrabi Province ranks fifth in tourism income in Thailand with six million arrivals. Only [[Bangkok]], [[Phuket]], [[Chonburi Province|Chonburi]], and [[Chiang Mai Province|Chiang Mai]] earn more from tourism. Arrivals are concentrated from November to April. The crush of high-season visitors has come at considerable cost to the environment. Local authorities have devised a program, \"Krabi 365 Days\" to move some high-season visitors to the off-season, from May to October, called the \"green season\" by tourism officials, partly due to the seasonal rains. Tourism revenue has grown at an average of eight percent annually. In 2018, tourism income is expected to hit 100 billion [[Thai baht|baht]], up from 96 billion in 2017. The top visitors are Chinese and Malaysians. Scandinavians number in the top five visiting nationalities. According to the [[Tourism Authority of Thailand]] (TAT) {{Asof|2018|lc=yes}} there are 460 hotels in the province, with some 200 additional hotels in the process of being licensed and another 200 in the preliminary stages of consideration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiriyapong |first1=Nareerat |title=Krabi pushes off-season arrivals |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1479141/krabi-pushes-off-season-arrivals |accessdate=5 June 2018 |work=Bangkok Post |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nSince 1999 the province has been served by the international [[Krabi International Airport]]. \n\n[[Phetkasem Road]] (Thailand Route 4) passes through the province.\n\n==Human achievement index 2017==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"width:400px;\"\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Health\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Education\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Employment\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Income\n|-\n| [[File:Health icon Thai.png|95px]]\n| [[File:Round Landmark School Icon - Transparent.svg|100px]]\n| [[File:Employment icon.png|100px]]\n| [[File:Numismatics and Notaphily icon.png|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 36\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 60\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 69\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 42 \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Housing\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Family\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Transport\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Participation \n|-\n| style=\"height:100px;\"| [[File:586-house-with-garden.svg|100px]] \n| [[File:Parents, enfants, famille.png|center|85px]]\n| [[File:Groundtransport inv.svg|100px]]\n| [[File:Icon Sociopol\u00edtica y relaciones internacionales (wikiproyect, es.wp).png|90px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 64\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 51\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 23\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 41  \n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"; style=\"background:black; color:white;\"| Province Krabi, with an HAI 2017 value of 0.5465 is \"low\", occupies place 66 in the ranking.\n|}\nSince 2003, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in Thailand has tracked progress on human development at sub-national level using the [[Human achievement index]] (HAI), a composite index covering all the eight key areas of human development. National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB) has taken over this task since 2017.<ref name=\"HAI 2560\" />\n{|---valign=top\n||Rank||Classification\n|-\n||&nbsp;&nbsp;1 - 15||\"high\"\n|-\n||16 - 30||\"somewhat high\"\n|-\n||31 - 45||\"average\"\n|-\n||45 - 60||\"somewhat low\"\n|-\n||61 - 77||\"low\"\n|}\n{|role= \"presentation\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|<strong>Map with provinces and HAI 2017 rankings</strong>\n|-\n|[[File:HAI 2017 rankings.png|750px]]\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Environment==\n[[File:Koh Ngai 07.jpg|thumb|right|Ko Ngai]]\nIn mid-2015, government plans to build an 800 [[megawatt]] coal-fired electricity generating station (EGAT Coal-Fired TH #3)<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary of Thailand Power Development Plan 2012 \u2013 2030 (PDP2010: Rev 3)|url=http://www.egat.co.th/en/images/about-egat/PDP2010-Rev3-Eng.pdf|website=Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand (EGAT)|publisher=Ministry of Energy, Energy Policy and Planning Office|accessdate=22 July 2015|page=13|date=June 2012}}</ref>{{rp|13}} in [[Tambon]] Pakasai in [[Amphoe Nuea Khlong]] have generated protests and hunger strikes by those opposed to the plant who say that it would endanger Krabi's relatively pristine environment. The [[Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand]] (EGAT) has pushed forward with development. The government intends to start the bidding process without an environmental assessment in order to \"save time\". The Krabi site is one of nine coal-fired plants planned for southern Thailand to be constructed over the next two decades to off-set the depletion of natural gas fields in the [[Gulf of Thailand]]. Opponents of the plan say their demands\u2014which include a three-year waiting period to see if the province can produce 100 percent renewable energy\u2014have been ignored.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andersen|first1=Ted|title=Hunger strikes, protests to oppose Thailand's plan for coal plants on Andaman Coast|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2015/07/21/coal-plant-proposed-for-pristine-thai-coast-sparks-outcry|accessdate=22 July 2015|work=U.S. News & World Report|agency=Associated Press|date=2015-07-21}}</ref>\n\nThailand's resolve to go ahead with the massive new coal-fired power station in Krabi, a 315 MWe, 48 billion baht undertaking, presents a problem. Coal is a major source of mercury poisoning and has been found in toxic amounts up to 12 times more than the maximum acceptable dose in the inhabitants of Tha Thum in [[Prachinburi Province]]. Possible vectors are fly ash from the local coal power plant, coal dust from outdoor coal storage piles, or coal ash, used as fertiliser. These present risks to Krabi. [[Coal pollution mitigation]] technology, sometimes called \"clean coal\", is still in its infancy and at the moment can only handle sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides, and particulates. Carbon dioxide sequestering is much more complex and costly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Draper|first1=John|last2=Kamnuansilpa|first2=Peerasit|title=Thailand's power dilemma amid a climate of fear|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/opinion/Thailands-power-dilemma-amid-a-climate-of-fear-30267497.html|accessdate=27 August 2015|work=The Nation|date=2015-08-27}}</ref><ref name=GP-2014>{{cite book|title=Paradise at Risk: The Krabi Coal-fired Power Plant Project|date=2014|publisher=Greenpeace Southeast Asia|location=Bangkok|url=http://tcc.greenpeace.or.th/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/ENGLISH-UPDATE.pdf|accessdate=14 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185253/http://tcc.greenpeace.or.th/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/ENGLISH-UPDATE.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Meigs|first1=James B|title=The Myth of Clean Coal: Analysis|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/energy/a4947/4339171/|accessdate=18 October 2016|work=Popular Mechanics|date=2011-07-14}}</ref> Two academics, referring to coal pollution mitigation in general, point out that, \"So-called 'clean coal' is expensive, untested, unwieldy and unworkable, yet it is raised as a panacea.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilder|first1=Robert|last2=Kammen|first2=Daniel M|title=Exposed: The Climate Fallacy of 2100|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/exposed-the-climate-fallacy-of-2100/|accessdate=21 October 2016|work=Scientific American|date=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ko Lanta Beach.jpg|thumb|right|Kantiang Bay in southern Ko Lanta Yai]]\nIn mid-2016, a pro-renewables working group in Krabi published a \"Green Power Development Plan\". It concludes that Krabi Province can depend on renewables\u2014mainly biomass and biogas\u2014for 100 percent of its electricity needs. The report calculates that biomass could generate 118 MW in an initial  three-year period; solar could generate 55 MW; biogas, 54 MW; and wind energy 40 MW. During a subsequent three-year period, renewables could generate 287 MW, exceeding the province's peak demand year of 2015, when it consumed 143 MW. If adopted, the plan would obviate the need to import coal, saving 175 billion baht over a 25-year period.<ref name=\"BP-20160820\">{{cite news|last1=Atthakor|first1=Ploenpote|title=Govt needs to get fired up over renewables|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1066584/govt-needs-to-get-fired-up-over-renewables|accessdate=25 August 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, EGAT solicited bids for the plant's construction and received bids in the range of 32\u201334.9 billion baht. The bidding process and the environmental and health impact assessment report were completed simultaneously. \"After being delayed for almost two years, this November [2016]  will be the time to decide whether to proceed or scrap the plan,\" said Energy Minister Gen Anantaporn Kanjanarat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Praiwan|first1=Yuthana|title=Call on Krabi coal plant due in November|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1101873/call-on-krabi-coal-plant-due-in-november|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nEGAT power plant opponents in Krabi have formed a coalition of local administration officials, academics, businesspersons, and concerned citizens that is proving to be a formidable opponent of EGAT's fossil fueled plans. Krabi is a leading tourist destination on the Andaman Coast. Local government has described coal as \"filthy\" and in conflict with tourism. The province has set itself the goal of being \"...solely dependent on renewable energy.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Going full steam ahead|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1314055/going-full-steam-ahead|accessdate=28 August 2017|work=Bangkok Post|date=28 August 2017|format=Editorial}}</ref>\n\n===Projected impact of changes in climate===\n[[File:White sand beach, Koh Poda tropical archipelago, Krabi, Thailand.jpg|thumb|right|Koh Poda]]\nIn a 2008 study of the impact of climate change on Krabi Province to the year 2033, the following effects were projected:<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|5,56}}\n\n* Temperature: The study forecasts modest temperature changes, slightly more than 1\u02daC at inland locations over the next 10\u201325 years. Coastal temperatures are projected to rise slightly less than 1\u02daC.\n* Rainfall: Annual monsoons will be two weeks shorter by 2018 and four weeks shorter by 2033. Total rainfall may decrease by 10 percent by 2033 according to the study.\n* Sea level: Sea level will rise substantially, with negative implications for Krabi's mangrove wetlands. The rise of mean sea level on the Krabi coastline is projected to rise by about 1&nbsp;cm annually over the next 25 years. A sea level rise of 20&nbsp;cm over the next 25 years would cause existing (2008) shorelines will retreat 10\u201335 m.\n* Tropical storms: Fewer [[cyclone]]s are forecasted, although higher sea levels may result in storms doing more damage to coastal infrastructure.\n\n==National park==\n* [[Hat Noppharat Thara\u2013Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park]] is a marine national park.<ref name=\"Braatz1992\">{{cite book|last=Braatz|first=Susan M.|title=Conserving biological diversity: a strategy for protected areas in the Asia-Pacific region|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6AN1_TnZkQsC&pg=PA57|accessdate=October 1, 2011|date=November 1992|publisher=World Bank Publications|isbn=978-0-8213-2307-6|pages=57\u2013}}</ref> Established in 1983, it is an [[IUCN]] Category II protected area with [[coral reef]]s, and an area measuring {{convert|387.9|km2}}.<ref name=DNP>{{cite web | title=Hat Noppharat Thara - Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park | url = http://www.dnp.go.th/parkreserve/asp/style1/default.asp?npid=35&lg=2 | website = Department of National Parks (DNP) Thailand | accessdate = 18 January 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223511/http://www.dnp.go.th/parkreserve/asp/style1/default.asp?npid=35&lg=2 | archivedate = 23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|File:KoPhiphi.jpg|1024px|3=<div align=center>The [[Ko Phi Phi Don]] is the largest of the islands in the [[Ko Phi Phi]] archipelago</div>|dir=rtl}}\n\n{{Gallery|title=Ko Phi Phi Le|width=170|height=120|lines=3|align=center\n| File:Isla Phi Phi Lay, Tailandia, 2013-08-19, DD 22.JPG|[[Crab-eating macaque]] (Macaca fascicularis)\n| File:Ko Phi Phi Le 4.jpg|View of the northern part of Ko Phi Phi Le\n| File:Isla Phi Phi Lay, Tailandia, 2013-08-19, DD 07.JPG|Phi Phi Le Island\n| File:Ko Phi Phi Leh definitive vertical limestone cliff as seen from the water, Thailand.jpg|Ko Phi Phi Le cliffs\n}}\n\n* [[Mu Ko Lanta National Park]] is a national park in the southern part of Krabi Province, consisting of several islands.  The two largest islands are Ko Lanta Noi and Ko Lanta Yai. Although both are inhabited, Ko Lanta Yai is the primary tourist destination. The park was established in 1990.\n\n{{Wide image|File:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-01.jpg|700px|3=<div align=center>Mu Ko Lanta National Park</div>|dir=rtl}}\n\n{{Gallery|title=Mu Ko Lanta|width=170|height=120|lines=3|align=center\n| File:Mu Ko Lanta National Park (2).jpg|Ko Lanta\n| File:\u0e1d\u0e39\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e32\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e39\u0e48\u0e40\u0e01\u0e32\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e32.jpg|[[Yellowstripe scad]] at Ko Lanta\n| File:Little crab.jpg|Little [[Crab]] at Ko Lanta\n}}\n\n==Sport==\n;Football\n\n[[Krabi F.C.|Krabi]] football club participates in [[Thai League 3]] Lower Region, the third tier of Thai football league system. The Andaman Eagles (Thai:\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e19\u0e14\u0e32\u0e21\u0e31\u0e19) plays their home matches at [[Krabi Provincial Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siamsport.co.th/football/thaileague2/view/51816|title=\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e40\u0e2d\u0e1f\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e42\u0e1c\u0e41\u0e02\u0e49\u0e07 32 \u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e25\u0e38\u0e22\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e0b\u0e31\u0e48\u0e192018}}</ref>\n\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Moo Koh PP4.JPG|[[Hat Noppharat Thara\u2013Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park]]\nFile:Longtail boat at Maya bay.JPG|Maya Bay\nFile:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-02.jpg|[[Mu Ko Lanta National Park]]\nFile:\u0e1b\u0e39\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e1b\u0e39\u0e21\u0e14\u0e41\u0e14\u0e07.jpg|[[Phricotelphusa limula]] in Mu Ko Lanta National Park\nFile:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-05.jpg|Ko Lanta\nFile:Walhai2.jpg|[[Whale shark]] at Phi Phi Island\nFile:Mushroom of the sea.jpg|Taken at a viewpoint on Phi Phi Leh island\nFile:2016 Prowincja Krabi, Ko Ngai (02).jpg|Ko Ngai\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\nReports (data) from Thai government are \"not copyrightable\" (Public Domain), Copyright Act 2537 (1994), section 7.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Thailand}}\n<!--Please do not add external links to hotel guides and similar, see the talk page of this article. This is not a travel guide nor a web directory. -->\n{{Commons category|Krabi Province}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Krabi Province}}\n*[http://www.krabi.go.th Provincial Website] {{in lang|th}}\n*[http://kanchanapisek.or.th/cgi-bin/kp8/oncc/province.cgi?prov=s1 Golden Jubilee Network province guide] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025192107/http://kanchanapisek.or.th/cgi-bin/kp8/oncc/province.cgi?prov=s1 |date=25 October 2014 }}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Krabi Province\n|North     = [[Surat Thani Province]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Nakhon Si Thammarat Province]]\n|Southeast = [[Trang Province]]\n|South     = \n|Southwest = [[Andaman Sea]]\n|West      = [[Phuket Province]]\n|Northwest = [[Phang Nga Province]]\n}}\n\n{{Provinces of Thailand}}\n\n{{coord|8|03|28|N|98|55|01|E|region:TH_type:adm1st|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Krabi Province| ]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Southern Thailand]]\n[[Category:Strait of Malacca]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{short description|Province of Thailand}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Krabi\n| native_name             = \u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48\n| native_name_lang        = th\n| settlement_type         = [[Provinces of Thailand|Province]]\n| image_skyline           = File:Poda island beach.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = The beach of Poda island with long-tail boats\n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_flag              = Krabi Flag.png\n| image_seal              = Seal Krabi.png\n| image_map               = Thailand Krabi locator map.svg\n| mapsize                 = frameless\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Map of Thailand highlighting Krabi Province\n| latd  =  |latm  =  |lats  =  |latNS  = \n| longd =  |longm =  |longs =  |longEW = \n| coordinates_type        = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = Thailand\n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = [[Krabi]]\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = Governor\n| leader_name             = Kitibadee Prawit<br>(since&nbsp;October 2017)\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=\"AREA\">{{cite report |title=Advancing Human Development through the ASEAN Community, Thailand Human Development Report 2014, table 0:Basic Data |url=http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/thailand_nhdr_2014_O.pdf |publisher=United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Thailand |pages=134-135 |access-date=17 January 2016 |isbn=978-974-680-368-7 |postscript=, Data has been supplied by Land Development Department, Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, at Wayback Machine.}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 4,709\n| area_rank               = [[Provinces of Thailand|Ranked 45th]]\n| area_water_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"TDD\">{{cite web ||url=http://stat.bora.dopa.go.th/stat/statnew/statTDD/ |title=\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e08\u0e33\u0e19\u0e27\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e08\u0e33\u0e1b\u0e35 \u0e1e.\u0e28.2561 |date=31 December 2018 |department=Registration Office Department of the Interior, Ministry of the Interior |language=Thai |trans-title=Statistics, population and house statistics for the year 2018 |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 473,738\n| population_as_of        = 2018\n| population_rank         = [[Provinces of Thailand| Ranked 59th]]\n| population_density_km2  = 101\n| population_density_rank = [[Provinces of Thailand|Ranked 49th]]\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = Human Achievement Index\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"HAI 2560\">[[:File:Human achievement index 2017.pdf|Human achievement index 2017 by National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB), pages 1-40, maps 1-9, retrieved 14 September 2019, ISBN 978-974-9769-33-1]]</ref>\n| demographics1_title1    = HAI (2017)\n| demographics1_info1     = 0.5465&nbsp;\"low\"<br/>[[Krabi Province#Human achievement index 2017|Ranked 66th]]\n| timezone1               = [[Time in Thailand|ICT]]\n| utc_offset1             = +7\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in Thailand|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 81xxx\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Thailand|Calling code]]\n| area_code               = 075\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:TH|TH-81]]\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.krabi.go.th}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Krabi''' ({{lang-th|\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48}} {{IPA-th|kr\u0101.b\u00ec\u02d0|pron}}, {{lang-sou|\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48}} {{IPA-th|kra.bi\u02d0|pron}}) is one of the southern [[Provinces of Thailand|provinces]] (''changwat'') of [[Thailand]], on the shore of the [[Andaman Sea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andaman Sea |url=https://www.google.com/maps/@7.6069786,98.3760131,9.25z |website=Google Maps |accessdate=2018-12-15}}</ref> Neighbouring provinces are (from north clockwise) [[Phang Nga province|Phang Nga]], [[Surat Thani province|Surat Thani]], [[Nakhon Si Thammarat province|Nakhon Si Thammarat]], and [[Trang province|Trang]]. [[Phuket Province]] lies to the west across [[Phang Nga Bay]]. [[Krabi]] town is the seat of provincial government.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Poda Island panorama.jpg|thumb|left|370px|Ko Poda seen from Ko Thap]]\nThe area is dotted with solitary [[limestone]] peaks, both on land and in the sea. Rock climbers from all over travel to Ton Sai Beach and [[Railay Beach]]. The beaches form part of Krabi's [[Phra Nang Peninsula]]. Of the 154 islands in the province, [[Ko Phi Phi Le]] is the most famous, as it was the site of the movie ''[[The Beach (film)|The Beach]]''. Other notable islands include [[Ko Phi Phi Don]], part of the [[Phi Phi Islands]], and [[Ko Lanta]], a larger island to the south. The coast was damaged by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|tsunami of 26 December 2004]].\n\nKrabi's limestone hills contain many caves, most having [[stalactite]]s and [[stalagmite]]s. Tham Chao Le and [[Tham Phi Hua To]], both in [[Amphoe Ao Luek|Ao Luek District]], contain prehistoric rock-paintings depicting humans, animals, and geometrical shapes. In Lang Rong Rien cave in 1986 archaeologists found 40,000-year-old human artifacts: stone tools, pottery, and bones. It is one of the oldest traces of human occupation in Southeast Asia. Krabi's caves are one of the main sources of nests of the [[Swiftlet|edible-nest swiftlet]], used in the making of [[bird's nest soup]].<ref>{{cite web|script-title=th:\u0e01\u0e25\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21 \u201c\u0e40\u0e25\u0e47\u0e01 \u0e2a\u0e15\u0e39\u0e25\u201d \u0e04\u0e27\u0e49\u0e32\u0e23\u0e31\u0e07\u0e19\u0e01\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48|url= https://www.thairath.co.th/content/532679|language=thai|date=2015-10-16|work=[[Thairath]]}}</ref>\n\nKrabi's farmland is dominated by a [[duopoly]] of [[natural rubber|rubber]] and [[palm oil]] plantations. Palm plantations alone occupy 980,000 [[rai (area)|rai]] (1,568&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), or 52 percent of the province's farmland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atthakor|first1=Ploenpote|title=Govt needs to get fired up over renewables|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1066584/govt-needs-to-get-fired-up-over-renewables|accessdate=20 August 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Together, palm oil and rubber cover 95 percent of Krabi's cultivated area with many smallholder farms amidst industrial plantations.<ref name=\"WWF\">{{cite book|last1=World Wildlife Fund Greater Mekong Program (WWF-GMP)|last2=South East Asian-Global Change System for Analysis, Research and Training organisation (SEA-START)|title=Climate Change Impacts in Krabi Province, Thailand. A study of environmental, social, and economic challenges|date=December 2008|url=http://startcc.iwlearn.org/doc/Doc_eng_11.pdf|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>{{RP|5}}\n\n==History==\nCirca 1200 CE, Krabi was tributary to the [[Thammarat kingdom|Kingdom of Ligor]], a city on the Kra Peninsula's east coast, better known today as Nakhon Si Thammarat. In modern times, Krabi was administered from Nakhon Si Thammarat, even after 1872 when King [[Chulalongkorn]] granted Krabi town status. In 1875 it was made a direct subordinate of Bangkok, becoming what is now a province. In 1900 the governor <!--[[Ratsadanupradit Mahison Phakdi|Phraya Ratsada Nupradit]] (Kho Sim Be na Ranong) --> moved the seat of the province from Ban Talad Kao to its present location at the mouth of the Krabi River.\n\nIt is believed the town may have taken its name from the word \"krabi\", which means 'sword'. This may stem from a legend that an ancient sword was unearthed prior to the city's founding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srikrabi.net/en/knowledge-detail.php?id=83|work=srikrabi|script-title=th:\u0e08\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48|language=thai}}</ref>\n\n==Symbols==\nThe [[Seals of The Provinces of Thailand|seal of the province]] shows two ancient crossed swords ([[krabi (sword)|''krabi'']] is a word for an ancient Siamese sword) in front of the [[Indian Ocean]] and [[Khao Phanom Bencha]] mountain which, at {{convert|1397|m|-1}} above sea level, is the highest mountain of the province.<ref name=OSMA>{{cite web|title=Symbol of Krabi|url=http://www.osmsouth-w.moi.go.th/osm-introduce.php?url=krabi-logo&l=en|website=OSM Andamnan: The Office of Strategy Management for Southern Province Cluster|accessdate=26 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234115/http://www.osmsouth-w.moi.go.th/osm-introduce.php?url=krabi-logo&l=en|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe provincial slogan is, \"Krabi, the liveable city, friendly people.\"<ref name=OSMA />\n\nThe provincial tree is the ''blue sky'' (Thai: thung-fa \u0e17\u0e38\u0e49\u0e07\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32) or ''[[Alstonia macrophylla]]''.\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n===Provincial government===\nKrabi is subdivided into eight districts (''[[amphoe]]''), which are further divided into 53 subdistricts (''[[tambon]]'') and 374 villages (''[[muban]]'').\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Map\n! Number\n! Name\n! Thai\n|-\n|rowspan=10|[[File:Amphoe Krabi.svg|170px]]\n|-\n||1||[[Amphoe Mueang Krabi|Mueang Krabi]]|| \u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48\n|-\n||2||[[Amphoe Khao Phanom|Khao Phanom]]|| \u0e40\u0e02\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e19\u0e21\n|-\n||3||[[Ko Lanta]] || \u0e40\u0e01\u0e32\u0e30\u0e25\u0e31\u0e19\u0e15\u0e32\n|-\n||4||[[Amphoe Khlong Thom|Khlong Thom]]|| \u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e21 \n|-\n||5||[[Amphoe Ao Luek|Ao Luek]]|| \u0e2d\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e25\u0e36\u0e01\n|-\n||6||[[Amphoe Plai Phraya|Plai Phraya]]|| \u0e1b\u0e25\u0e32\u0e22\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e22\u0e32\n|-\n||7||[[Amphoe Lam Thap|Lam Thap]]|| \u0e25\u0e33\u0e17\u0e31\u0e1a\n|-\n||8||[[Amphoe Nuea Khlong|Nuea Khlong]]|| \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07\n|}\n===Local government===\nAs of 26 November 2019 there are<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dla.go.th/work/abt/province.jsp |title=Number of local government organizations by province |date=26 November 2019 |website=dla.go.th |publisher=Department of Local Administration (DLA) |access-date=10 December 2019 | quote=1 Krabi: 1 PAO, 1 Town mun., 12 Subdistrict mun., 48 SAO.}}</ref>: one Krabi Provincial Administration Organisation (''ongkan borihan suan changwat'') and 13 municipal (''thesaban'') areas in the province. Krabi has town (''[[thesaban mueang]]'') status. Further 12 subdistrict municipalities (''[[thesaban tambon]]''). The non-municipal areas are administered by 48 Subdistrict Administrative Organisations - SAO (''ongkan borihan suan tambon'').<ref name=\"TDD\"/>\n\n== Population and culture ==\nKrabi's population includes Buddhists, Thai-Chinese, [[Moken|Moken (sea gypsies)]], and Muslims. Population is most dense in the coastal area in [[Nuea Khlong District]] and [[Mueang Krabi District|Krabi city districts]], both with population densities above 150 people per km<sup>2</sup>. The least densely populated area is the inland mountain [[Khao Phanom District]] at 61 persons per km<sup>2</sup>. Buddhism is the religion most observed (66 percent) followed by Islam (33 percent). Krabi has been little affected by the Muslim militant insurgency that has plagued the southern provinces of Thailand since 2003. Traditionally Krabi's inhabitants worked in agriculture, for the province is rich in rubber, palm oil, and oranges. In recent years tourism has become an important source of income.<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|7}}\n\n==Economy==\nAgriculture, tourism, and, to a lesser extent, fisheries, form the backbone of Krabi's economy.<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|18\u201319}} Rubber is the primary cash crop of the province, followed by palm oil. Thailand's largest producer of palm oil products, Univanich Palm Oil PCL, is headquartered in Krabi. It employs 1,000 persons directly and purchases feed stock from 2,000 small and medium-sized Krabi growers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://univanich.com/product.htm|website=Univanich Palm Oil PCL|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Ko Phi Phi after sunset, preparing for the night.JPG|thumb|Sunset, Ko Phi Phi]]\nKrabi Province ranks fifth in tourism income in Thailand with six million arrivals. Only [[Bangkok]], [[Phuket]], [[Chonburi Province|Chonburi]], and [[Chiang Mai Province|Chiang Mai]] earn more from tourism. Arrivals are concentrated from November to April. The crush of high-season visitors has come at considerable cost to the environment. Local authorities have devised a program, \"Krabi 365 Days\" to move some high-season visitors to the off-season, from May to October, called the \"green season\" by tourism officials, partly due to the seasonal rains. Tourism revenue has grown at an average of eight percent annually. In 2018, tourism income is expected to hit 100 billion [[Thai baht|baht]], up from 96 billion in 2017. The top visitors are Chinese and Malaysians. Scandinavians number in the top five visiting nationalities. According to the [[Tourism Authority of Thailand]] (TAT) {{Asof|2018|lc=yes}} there are 460 hotels in the province, with some 200 additional hotels in the process of being licensed and another 200 in the preliminary stages of consideration.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wiriyapong |first1=Nareerat |title=Krabi pushes off-season arrivals |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1479141/krabi-pushes-off-season-arrivals |accessdate=5 June 2018 |work=Bangkok Post |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nSince 1999 the province has been served by the international [[Krabi International Airport]]. \n\n[[Phetkasem Road]] (Thailand Route 4) passes through the province.\n\n==Human achievement index 2017==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"width:400px;\"\n|- \n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Health\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Education\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Employment\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:100px; background:black; color:white;\"| Income\n|-\n| [[File:Health icon Thai.png|95px]]\n| [[File:Round Landmark School Icon - Transparent.svg|100px]]\n| [[File:Employment icon.png|100px]]\n| [[File:Numismatics and Notaphily icon.png|100px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 36\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 60\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 69\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 42 \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Housing\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Family\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Transport\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| Participation \n|-\n| style=\"height:100px;\"| [[File:586-house-with-garden.svg|100px]] \n| [[File:Parents, enfants, famille.png|center|85px]]\n| [[File:Groundtransport inv.svg|100px]]\n| [[File:Icon Sociopol\u00edtica y relaciones internacionales (wikiproyect, es.wp).png|90px]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 64\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 51\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 23\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:black; color:white;\"| 41  \n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"; style=\"background:black; color:white;\"| Province Krabi, with an HAI 2017 value of 0.5465 is \"low\", occupies place 66 in the ranking.\n|}\nSince 2003, United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) in Thailand has tracked progress on human development at sub-national level using the [[Human achievement index]] (HAI), a composite index covering all the eight key areas of human development. National Economic and Social Development Board (NESDB) has taken over this task since 2017.<ref name=\"HAI 2560\" />\n{|---valign=top\n||Rank||Classification\n|-\n||&nbsp;&nbsp;1 - 15||\"high\"\n|-\n||16 - 30||\"somewhat high\"\n|-\n||31 - 45||\"average\"\n|-\n||45 - 60||\"somewhat low\"\n|-\n||61 - 77||\"low\"\n|}\n{|role= \"presentation\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|<strong>Map with provinces and HAI 2017 rankings</strong>\n|-\n|[[File:HAI 2017 rankings.png|750px]]\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Environment==\n[[File:Koh Ngai 07.jpg|thumb|right|Ko Ngai]]\nIn mid-2015, government plans to build an 800 [[megawatt]] coal-fired electricity generating station (EGAT Coal-Fired TH #3)<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary of Thailand Power Development Plan 2012 \u2013 2030 (PDP2010: Rev 3)|url=http://www.egat.co.th/en/images/about-egat/PDP2010-Rev3-Eng.pdf|website=Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand (EGAT)|publisher=Ministry of Energy, Energy Policy and Planning Office|accessdate=22 July 2015|page=13|date=June 2012}}</ref>{{rp|13}} in [[Tambon]] Pakasai in [[Amphoe Nuea Khlong]] have generated protests and hunger strikes by those opposed to the plant who say that it would endanger Krabi's relatively pristine environment. The [[Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand]] (EGAT) has pushed forward with development. The government intends to start the bidding process without an environmental assessment in order to \"save time\". The Krabi site is one of nine coal-fired plants planned for southern Thailand to be constructed over the next two decades to off-set the depletion of natural gas fields in the [[Gulf of Thailand]]. Opponents of the plan say their demands\u2014which include a three-year waiting period to see if the province can produce 100 percent renewable energy\u2014have been ignored.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andersen|first1=Ted|title=Hunger strikes, protests to oppose Thailand's plan for coal plants on Andaman Coast|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2015/07/21/coal-plant-proposed-for-pristine-thai-coast-sparks-outcry|accessdate=22 July 2015|work=U.S. News & World Report|agency=Associated Press|date=2015-07-21}}</ref>\n\nThailand's resolve to go ahead with the massive new coal-fired power station in Krabi, a 315 MWe, 48 billion baht undertaking, presents a problem. Coal is a major source of mercury poisoning and has been found in toxic amounts up to 12 times more than the maximum acceptable dose in the inhabitants of Tha Thum in [[Prachinburi Province]]. Possible vectors are fly ash from the local coal power plant, coal dust from outdoor coal storage piles, or coal ash, used as fertiliser. These present risks to Krabi. [[Coal pollution mitigation]] technology, sometimes called \"clean coal\", is still in its infancy and at the moment can only handle sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides, and particulates. Carbon dioxide sequestering is much more complex and costly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Draper|first1=John|last2=Kamnuansilpa|first2=Peerasit|title=Thailand's power dilemma amid a climate of fear|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/opinion/Thailands-power-dilemma-amid-a-climate-of-fear-30267497.html|accessdate=27 August 2015|work=The Nation|date=2015-08-27}}</ref><ref name=GP-2014>{{cite book|title=Paradise at Risk: The Krabi Coal-fired Power Plant Project|date=2014|publisher=Greenpeace Southeast Asia|location=Bangkok|url=http://tcc.greenpeace.or.th/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/ENGLISH-UPDATE.pdf|accessdate=14 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304185253/http://tcc.greenpeace.or.th/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/ENGLISH-UPDATE.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Meigs|first1=James B|title=The Myth of Clean Coal: Analysis|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/energy/a4947/4339171/|accessdate=18 October 2016|work=Popular Mechanics|date=2011-07-14}}</ref> Two academics, referring to coal pollution mitigation in general, point out that, \"So-called 'clean coal' is expensive, untested, unwieldy and unworkable, yet it is raised as a panacea.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilder|first1=Robert|last2=Kammen|first2=Daniel M|title=Exposed: The Climate Fallacy of 2100|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/exposed-the-climate-fallacy-of-2100/|accessdate=21 October 2016|work=Scientific American|date=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ko Lanta Beach.jpg|thumb|right|Kantiang Bay in southern Ko Lanta Yai]]\nIn mid-2016, a pro-renewables working group in Krabi published a \"Green Power Development Plan\". It concludes that Krabi Province can depend on renewables\u2014mainly biomass and biogas\u2014for 100 percent of its electricity needs. The report calculates that biomass could generate 118 MW in an initial  three-year period; solar could generate 55 MW; biogas, 54 MW; and wind energy 40 MW. During a subsequent three-year period, renewables could generate 287 MW, exceeding the province's peak demand year of 2015, when it consumed 143 MW. If adopted, the plan would obviate the need to import coal, saving 175 billion baht over a 25-year period.<ref name=\"BP-20160820\">{{cite news|last1=Atthakor|first1=Ploenpote|title=Govt needs to get fired up over renewables|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1066584/govt-needs-to-get-fired-up-over-renewables|accessdate=25 August 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, EGAT solicited bids for the plant's construction and received bids in the range of 32\u201334.9 billion baht. The bidding process and the environmental and health impact assessment report were completed simultaneously. \"After being delayed for almost two years, this November [2016]  will be the time to decide whether to proceed or scrap the plan,\" said Energy Minister Gen Anantaporn Kanjanarat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Praiwan|first1=Yuthana|title=Call on Krabi coal plant due in November|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1101873/call-on-krabi-coal-plant-due-in-november|accessdate=4 October 2016|work=Bangkok Post|date=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nEGAT power plant opponents in Krabi have formed a coalition of local administration officials, academics, businesspersons, and concerned citizens that is proving to be a formidable opponent of EGAT's fossil fueled plans. Krabi is a leading tourist destination on the Andaman Coast. Local government has described coal as \"filthy\" and in conflict with tourism. The province has set itself the goal of being \"...solely dependent on renewable energy.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Going full steam ahead|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1314055/going-full-steam-ahead|accessdate=28 August 2017|work=Bangkok Post|date=28 August 2017|format=Editorial}}</ref>\n\n===Projected impact of changes in climate===\n[[File:White sand beach, Koh Poda tropical archipelago, Krabi, Thailand.jpg|thumb|right|Koh Poda]]\nIn a 2008 study of the impact of climate change on Krabi Province to the year 2033, the following effects were projected:<ref name=\"WWF\" />{{RP|5,56}}\n\n* Temperature: The study forecasts modest temperature changes, slightly more than 1\u02daC at inland locations over the next 10\u201325 years. Coastal temperatures are projected to rise slightly less than 1\u02daC.\n* Rainfall: Annual monsoons will be two weeks shorter by 2018 and four weeks shorter by 2033. Total rainfall may decrease by 10 percent by 2033 according to the study.\n* Sea level: Sea level will rise substantially, with negative implications for Krabi's mangrove wetlands. The rise of mean sea level on the Krabi coastline is projected to rise by about 1&nbsp;cm annually over the next 25 years. A sea level rise of 20&nbsp;cm over the next 25 years would cause existing (2008) shorelines will retreat 10\u201335 m.\n* Tropical storms: Fewer [[cyclone]]s are forecasted, although higher sea levels may result in storms doing more damage to coastal infrastructure.\n\n==National park==\n* [[Hat Noppharat Thara\u2013Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park]] is a marine national park.<ref name=\"Braatz1992\">{{cite book|last=Braatz|first=Susan M.|title=Conserving biological diversity: a strategy for protected areas in the Asia-Pacific region|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6AN1_TnZkQsC&pg=PA57|accessdate=October 1, 2011|date=November 1992|publisher=World Bank Publications|isbn=978-0-8213-2307-6|pages=57\u2013}}</ref> Established in 1983, it is an [[IUCN]] Category II protected area with [[coral reef]]s, and an area measuring {{convert|387.9|km2}}.<ref name=DNP>{{cite web | title=Hat Noppharat Thara - Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park | url = http://www.dnp.go.th/parkreserve/asp/style1/default.asp?npid=35&lg=2 | website = Department of National Parks (DNP) Thailand | accessdate = 18 January 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223511/http://www.dnp.go.th/parkreserve/asp/style1/default.asp?npid=35&lg=2 | archivedate = 23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Wide image|File:KoPhiphi.jpg|1024px|3=<div align=center>The [[Ko Phi Phi Don]] is the largest of the islands in the [[Ko Phi Phi]] archipelago</div>|dir=rtl}}\n\n{{Gallery|title=Ko Phi Phi Le|width=170|height=120|lines=3|align=center\n| File:Isla Phi Phi Lay, Tailandia, 2013-08-19, DD 22.JPG|[[Crab-eating macaque]] (Macaca fascicularis)\n| File:Ko Phi Phi Le 4.jpg|View of the northern part of Ko Phi Phi Le\n| File:Isla Phi Phi Lay, Tailandia, 2013-08-19, DD 07.JPG|Phi Phi Le Island\n| File:Ko Phi Phi Leh definitive vertical limestone cliff as seen from the water, Thailand.jpg|Ko Phi Phi Le cliffs\n}}\n\n* [[Mu Ko Lanta National Park]] is a national park in the southern part of Krabi Province, consisting of several islands.  The two largest islands are Ko Lanta Noi and Ko Lanta Yai. Although both are inhabited, Ko Lanta Yai is the primary tourist destination. The park was established in 1990.\n\n{{Wide image|File:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-01.jpg|700px|3=<div align=center>Mu Ko Lanta National Park</div>|dir=rtl}}\n\n{{Gallery|title=Mu Ko Lanta|width=170|height=120|lines=3|align=center\n| File:Mu Ko Lanta National Park (2).jpg|Ko Lanta\n| File:\u0e1d\u0e39\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e25\u0e32\u0e02\u0e49\u0e32\u0e07\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e39\u0e48\u0e40\u0e01\u0e32\u0e30\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e32.jpg|[[Yellowstripe scad]] at Ko Lanta\n| File:Little crab.jpg|Little [[Crab]] at Ko Lanta\n}}\n\n==Sport==\n;Football\n\n[[Krabi F.C.|Krabi]] football club participates in [[Thai League 3]] Lower Region, the third tier of Thai football league system. The Andaman Eagles (Thai:\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e19\u0e17\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e19\u0e14\u0e32\u0e21\u0e31\u0e19) plays their home matches at [[Krabi Provincial Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siamsport.co.th/football/thaileague2/view/51816|title=\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e1a\u0e35\u0e48 \u0e40\u0e2d\u0e1f\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e41\u0e1a\u0e42\u0e1c\u0e41\u0e02\u0e49\u0e07 32 \u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e25\u0e38\u0e22\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e0b\u0e31\u0e48\u0e192018}}</ref>\n\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Moo Koh PP4.JPG|[[Hat Noppharat Thara\u2013Mu Ko Phi Phi National Park]]\nFile:Longtail boat at Maya bay.JPG|Maya Bay\nFile:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-02.jpg|[[Mu Ko Lanta National Park]]\nFile:\u0e1b\u0e39\u0e17\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e1b\u0e39\u0e21\u0e14\u0e41\u0e14\u0e07.jpg|[[Phricotelphusa limula]] in Mu Ko Lanta National Park\nFile:1062-mu-koh-lanta-national-park-05.jpg|Ko Lanta\nFile:Walhai2.jpg|[[Whale shark]] at Phi Phi Island\nFile:Mushroom of the sea.jpg|Taken at a viewpoint on Phi Phi Leh island\nFile:2016 Prowincja Krabi, Ko Ngai (02).jpg|Ko Ngai\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\nReports (data) from Thai government are \"not copyrightable\" (Public Domain), Copyright Act 2537 (1994), section 7.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Thailand}}\n<!--Please do not add external links to hotel guides and similar, see the talk page of this article. This is not a travel guide nor a web directory. -->\n{{Commons category|Krabi Province}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Krabi Pro